[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The world faces major challenges – from climate change, to resource use, to
[normal] population growth and
[normal] changing demographics – and these are creating 
[normal]challenges for the 
[normal]global
[normal] economy and 
[normal]market opportunities for new 
[normal]technology 
[normal]solutions. 
[normal] 
[normal]Failing to respond t
[normal]o these challenges would have 
[normal]a 
[normal]significant impact on our everyday lives.  Energy plays a vital role in the UK economy
[normal] and it is essential for us to maintain affordable and secure supplies for the future.
[normal]2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Technological i
[normal]nnovation in the energy sector can b
[normal]e defined as the application of new and improved technologies to increase the efficiency and reduce the cost of extracting, generating, distributing and using energy. 
[normal]Bringing
[normal] these technologies to market 
[normal]is 
[normal]often too expensive and risky for industry to de
[normal]liver them alone. 
[normal] In the case of academic research
[normal],
[normal] private companies are 
[normal]rarely
[normal] incentivised to engage in such activities
[normal] without public sector intervention and support
[normal]. 
[normal] Even later stage innovation is often too expensive and risky for companies to engag
[normal]e in alone
[normal] where costs to commercialise a new product may run to tens of millions over many years
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]  
[normal]Public funding acts as an enabler in de-risking investment, through mechanisms such as grants which part fund the development of technologies
[normal] along
[normal]side
[normal] pri
[normal]vate sector investment
[normal]. 
[normal]3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In order to deliver its objectives, Government 
[normal]provides
[normal] support
[normal] and incentives
[normal] for 
[normal]the research, 
[normal]development
[normal], demonstration
[normal] and deployment of innovative technologies
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]LCICG
[normal] has a proactive low carbon innovation 
[normal]agenda
[normal] 
[normal]which is
[normal] 
[normal]focus
[normal]s
[normal]ed on delivering
[normal] 
[normal]government policy
[normal] objectives
[normal], including
[normal]:
[normal]5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Government’s policy is to 
[normal]ensure the UK 
[normal]can develop and deploy
[normal] the energy technologies
[normal] required to deliver on its economic and 
[normal]low 
[normal]carbon objectives
[normal]. 
[normal]These technologies cover a range of sectors, including energy generation, industrial energy 
[normal]efficiency, heat and built environment, and transport.
[normal] 
[normal]Government
[normal] targets public sector incentives on technologies 
[normal]that
[normal] 
[normal]would not be delivered by the market alone a
[normal]nd 
[normal]which 
[normal]can also provide wider societal benefits, such as knowledge and learning, reduced energy costs, employment and exports
[normal].  
[normal] 
[normal]6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The UK will not meet its low carbon targets with current technologies at today’s costs.  Innovation in low carbon technologies is essential if we are to transition to a low carbon society cost effectively.  
[normal]Given its scale, complexity and interdependencies
[normal], the energy system can neither be transformed quickly nor by a single “silver bullet”. Rather, innovation must occur across a broad front 
[normal]from generation through to use, at a component and system level.
[normal]  
[normal]7.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Low carbon technologies can take decades to develo
[normal]p, with inherently high costs and risks during pre-commercial stages. 
[normal]Market failures and barriers include p
[normal]oor market signals, long payback periods, under-developed supply chains
[normal],
[normal] and knowledge spill-overs that make it cheaper to replicate existing techno
[normal]logies than to develop 
[normal]them
[normal] from scratch. 
[normal]These
[normal] barriers have meant that businesses have tended to under-invest in low carbon innovation
[normal].  
[normal] At the same time, while market incentives provide confidence to technology developers that there will be a return on
[normal] investment, in many cases these are not 
[normal]sufficient t
[normal]o drive the required innovation.  Low carbon innovation is normally taken forwards by different businesses with different skills sets to those deploying the technologies which receive incentives.
[normal] 
[normal]For exa
[normal]mple, bioenergy technologies requires considerable up-front investment across the entire agricultural supply and value chain to realise future benefits as well as investor confidence and a 
[normal]supportive policy environment.  To fully realise the benefits will 
[normal]require a thirty year time horizon, but 
[normal]once established the returns from well managed energy crops are effectively sustainable indefinitely.
[normal]8.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]For these reasons, 
[normal]public sector
[normal] investment is a critical component in addressing market failures, managing risk a
[normal]nd achieving technological breakthroughs, while leveraging substantial funding from the private sector or other governments. 
[normal]Publicly funded programmes
[normal] range from fully funding the most uncertain phases of primary research through to joint funding and risk
[normal] sharing in the later stages, as technologies approach commercialisation. 
[normal]9.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The aim of these policies and programmes is to take key technologies to the point at which they are sufficiently proven
[normal], that the market,
[normal] 
[normal]potentially 
[normal]with the support of market mech
[normal]anisms
[normal] (such as the Renewables Obligation), or in partnership with the Green Investment Bank can
[normal] deploy them widely. 
[normal]Innovation can support growth and deployment by reducing risk and costs by :
[normal]This section provide
[normal]s
[normal] evidence against the Committee’s 
[normal]question
[normal] 4
[normal]: 
[normal]Are the Government &amp; LCICG targeting investment towards the most effective stages of the 
[normal]innovation process, including over the long-term?
[normal] [bold]10.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Government
[normal] 
[normal]s
[normal]upports
[normal] UK based companies 
[normal]to 
[normal]develop low carbon innovation technologies.  The funding is focussed on developing low carbon technologies which 
[normal]deliver economic benefit to the UK and
[normal]/or
[normal] reduce the cost of energy
[normal] while reduc
[normal]ing greenhouse gas emissions to meet legally binding targets
[normal] that stretch out to 2050
[normal].  
[normal]The energy system is highly complex with multiple technologies interacting through multip
[normal]le interfaces. Supporting innovation across the whole energy system and the full innovation journey is therefore also complicated. Energy also touches on many government policies and priorities including 
[normal]I
[normal]ndustrial 
[normal]Strategy
[normal], regional economies, environment
[normal], housing and transport. No single support mechanism or programme could deliver the range of support needed to deliver the diversity and scale of technology innovation required across the system.
[normal]11.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Government support therefore is provided in a range of ways 
[normal]by a range of Departments and Agencies
[normal]. 
[normal]Funding for low carbon innovation 
[normal]in the UK 
[normal]is primarily channelled
[normal] through the Department for Business
[normal],
[normal] Innovation and Skills (BIS), the Department for Energy and Climate Change (DECC)
[normal], and the Scottish Government
[normal].  
[normal] 
[normal]The following section sets out the
[normal] roles of these organisations, 
[normal]and
[normal] 
[normal]the organisations they sponsor, which 
[normal]together 
[normal]make up the core membership of the 
[normal]Low Carbon Innovation Coordination Group[bold] (LCICG).
[normal]In addition, associate members of the LCICG also play a fundamental role within the innovation landscape, such include Ofgem, which manages 
[normal]the £500m Low Carbon Ne
[normal]tworks Fund
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]Figure1: HMG low carbon energy innovation[bold] sponsors and the technology stages they are most engaged in[bold]       
[normal]12.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]BIS[bold] 
[normal]mainly delivers its energy innovation support activities through its arms
[normal]’
[normal] length 
[normal]bodies
[normal] 
[normal]- 
[normal]the Research Councils UK (RCUK), 
[normal]the 
[normal]Technology Strategy Board
[normal],
[normal] and 
[normal]a public-private partnership -
[normal] the
[normal] Energy Technologies Institute
[normal] (ETI)
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]BIS also run schemes, including the Regional Growth Fund
[normal] and Advanced Manufacturing Supply Chain Initiative
[normal], which 
[normal]are not innovation specific
[normal],
[normal] but 
[normal]are 
[normal]open to innovative businesses. 
[normal]13.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]Scottish Government[bold] also has arms’ length bodies with funding 
[normal]predominantly
[normal] channelled through 
[normal]Scottish Enterprise[bold] [bold]and 
[normal]Highlands and Islands Enterprise[bold].  
[normal]14.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] 
[normal]DECC
[normal]’s
[normal] innovation 
[normal]support 
[normal]i
[normal]s 
[normal]largely
[normal] d
[normal]elivered 
[normal]by an 
[normal]in-house
[normal] 
[normal]team
[normal] with some
[normal] programmes
[normal] being delivered in partnership with the 
[normal] 
[normal]Technology Strategy Board
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]E
[normal]xception
[normal]s are
[normal] DECC-
[normal]Carbon Trust
[normal] 
[normal]legacy
[normal] 
[normal]programmes
[normal],
[normal] which
[normal] 
[normal]includ
[normal]es
[normal] industr
[normal]y
[normal] led accelerator programme
[normal]s for technologies such as
[normal] offshore wind
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]15.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]DECC and [bold]the [bold]ETI[bold] are the only
[normal] core
[normal] LCICG members which 
[normal]solely 
[normal]have a
[normal]n
[normal] energy focus with both seeking to reduce the cost of energy
[normal] as their primary innovation objective
[normal].  DECC and ETI offer different but complementary approaches to innovati
[normal]on support
[normal] represented by their differ
[normal]ing
[normal] skills mix and governances
[normal].  
[normal]16.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]DECC supports innovation by inviting companies to express interest in specific “technology calls” such as components for offshore wind turbines and assesses bids based on their merits.
[normal]  Most of its funding is 
[normal]aimed at
[normal] later stage innovation to support the demonstration of technologies.  DECC provides grants to companies which part fund the development of the technology (in line with European state aid rules) and incubation support to he
[normal]lp smaller companies develop sufficient skills to commercialise technologies. 
[normal]17.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] [bold]The [bold]ETI[bold] is a public-private partnership which receives half of its funding from Government and the remainder from 7 large industrial companies (BP, Caterpillar, EDF, E.ON, Roll
[normal]s Royce, Shell and Hitachi).  The ETI seeks to identify solutions to a particular technology issue
[normal]s
[normal], such as a novel floating wind turbine.  Its solutions 
[normal]generally 
[normal]follow a procurement approach where it invite
[normal]s
[normal] companies 
[normal]and academia 
[normal]to submit proposals t
[normal]o demonstrate how they would deliver the 
[normal]output the ETI seeks
[normal],
[normal] or it 
[normal]target
[normal]s
[normal] business development approaches such as taking 
[normal]equity stakes in businesses while providing direct input into how the business 
[normal]is 
[normal]run
[normal].
[normal]18.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]RCUK[bold] and 
[normal]T[bold]echnology Strategy Board[bold] 
[normal]both 
[normal]adopt an interdisciplinary approach to enabling technology
[normal] innovation.  They 
[normal]prioritise
[normal] their in
[normal]novation on different stages 
[normal]of development and audiences.  
[normal]RCUK 
[normal]funds energy research in early stage technologies to help define and underpin future energy sup
[normal]ply options; enhance the understanding of the social, environmental and economic implications of future energy options; reduce energy consumption and demand through the development of behavioural, governance, market and technological advances; and build ca
[normal]pacity of skilled people.  
[normal] 
[normal]More information on RCUK’s energy programme can be found at Annex A.
[normal]19.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]T
[normal]he 
[normal]Technology Strategy Board
[normal] 
[normal]is 
[normal]the UK innovation agency, stimulating economic growth by helping UK businesses innovate more effectively.  It 
[normal]provides funding
[normal] and collaboration support
[normal] across the 
[normal]UK 
[normal]economy, with energy
[normal], built environment and low carbon transport
[normal] being 
[normal]amongst its key
[normal] 
[normal]focus areas.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]20.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Scottish Enterprise’s focus is on stimulating economic growth; exploiting low carbon opportunities; improving Sco
[normal]tland’s business infrastructure; and supporting business
[normal], with Wales and Northern Ireland’s governments having similar interests within their own geographical boundaries
[normal].
[normal]21.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Other members of the 
[normal]LCICG
[normal] which form the “associate” membership 
[normal]typically 
[normal]prioritise
[normal] on a sub-set of technologies and/or do not focus
[normal] on providing direct funding support
[normal], such as grants
[normal],
[normal] to aid technology development,
[normal] but have other innovation
[normal]-
[normal]enabling levers.  For example, the Crown Estate
[normal]’s offshore wind
[normal] 
[normal]test and demonstration leasing p
[normal]rogramme facilitate
[normal]s
[normal] successful demonstration of technology breakthroughs, through existing sites, new sites and non-grid sites, 
[normal]allowing offshore wind manufacturers greater flexibility to deploy and test wind turbines alongside existing projects in UK wat
[normal]ers.  The Department for Communities and Local Government uses
[normal] regulation and policy to ensure the construction of low carbon buildings
[normal]. The Department for Transport has a renewable transport policy including support for the most sustainable biofuels, in a
[normal]ddition to innovation in freight and low emission vehicles.
[normal] The Welsh Government , with ‘low carbon , energy and environment’ as one of its three science grand challenges, makes extensive
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] use of its EU Structural Fund programmes to support low carbon innovation.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]22.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Government and members of the LCICG have strategies and delivery plans which have been developed with and disseminated to the low carbon sector.  The LCICG will develop a shared strategy in 
[normal]early 2014 
[normal]which 
[normal]defines the agreed priorities for future programm
[normal]e delivery.
[normal]23.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Significant public sector RD&amp;D investment in low carbon technologies is needed to accelerate deployment and to capture economic gains. With constrained resour
[normal]ces, government needs to prioritise and target its investments in those technology areas that promise to deliver maximum value both in terms of cost, carbon savings, and economic impact
[normal] for the UK
[normal].
[normal]  Inevitably some technologies will be required to be bough
[normal]t in from abroad.
[normal]  
[normal]24.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]TINA project was launched in autumn 2010 
[normal]by
[normal] LCICG, combined with input from sector experts and organisations. Its aim is to create a robust shared knowledge base to inform coordinated programme planning and to support a portfolio ap
[normal]proach to innovation investments. The TINAs consolidate existing research and experience across government and apply a consistent methodology to identify and value the potential for innovation within those technologies likely to be most important in achiev
[normal]ing our energy and emissions targets and in delivering economic benefits. For each selected technology area, the TINAs identify key innovation needs out to 2050, including an assessment of:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]25.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The TINAs have already been used extensively by a number of LCICG organisations, for example in 
[normal]the development of current programmes, in the drafting of strategy documents such as the Off-shore Wind Industrial Strategy and in the des
[normal]ign and launch of specific initiatives such as the Off-shore Renewables Catapult
[normal].
[normal]26.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The TINAs
[normal] focus
[normal] on those technologies that previous modelling and analysis (by individual LCICG members, the Energy Research Partnership and the Committee on Climate Change) 
[normal]suggested were of particular importance to government objectives
[normal] and where significant and coordinated UK government support was likely needed. These are:
[normal]Bioenergy
[normal]Carbon Capture and Storage
[normal]Domestic Buildings
[normal]Electricity Networks and Storage
[normal]Heat
[normal]Hydrogen for Transport
[normal]Industrial 
[normal]Processes
[normal]Marine
[normal]Non-domestic Buildings
[normal]Nuclear Fission
[normal]Offshore Wind
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]27.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This is not 
[normal]intended to be 
[normal]a definitive list
[normal] 
[normal]of all technology families that could contribute to the UK’s energy and growth objectives. 
[normal]The LCICG
[normal] 
[normal]continue
[normal] to monitor technology developments
[normal] and we will expand the TINA evidence base to include other technologies if 
[normal]the Group identifies
[normal] a need for TINA 
[normal]analysis.
[normal] 
[normal]Currently 
[normal]3 areas for further work – Solar PV, Industrial CCS and Heat Networks – 
[normal]are bein
[normal]g considered for
[normal] 2014.
[normal]28.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Building on 
[normal]the LCICG’s joint work to date the LCICG members are drafting a strategic document that will help the Group work closely together to develop its future work programmes. That document will
[normal] describe ho
[normal]w public 
[normal]sector-
[normal]backed innovation support is delivered in the UK, summarise the progress made to date in strengthening coordination, 
[normal]will
[normal] set out 
[normal]the Group’s
[normal] shared aims and objectives and 
[normal]will 
[normal]detail how 
[normal]the Group
[normal] plan to work together to further strength
[normal]en 
[normal]their
[normal] coordination and impact in the future.
[normal]29.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Prioritising our resources on those innovations where the need is most pressing and where our investment can have the most impact is a key challenge for the Group. 
[normal]The 
[normal]TINAs
[normal] described above
[normal] analysed and quantified the impact of technology innovation needs for a dozen technology sectors
[normal]. The 
[normal]document 
[normal]will 
[normal]take that analysis a step 
[normal]further by
[normal] set
[normal]ting
[normal] out what 
[normal]the Group
[normal] believe are the key innovation needs in each of those dozen technology sectors and assess
[normal]ing
[normal] the scale of support that would be needed to address those needs.  
[normal]30.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The document will provide a framework for future prioritisation
[normal],
[normal] it will not however set out a
[normal] prioritised work programme. The UK government alone cannot support all the innovation needs identified and difficult choices will have to be made. 
[normal]T
[normal]hose choices will need to be informed by the success or otherwise of current innovation programmes, the dev
[normal]elopment of the technologies over the next few years, the development of wider energy policy and the availability of funding in future spending rounds. The future investment decisions made by members of the Group will be informed by the analysis in the doc
[normal]ument and the principles set out in it.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]31.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As outlined in the NAO
[normal]’s Public Funding for Innovation in Low Carbon Technologies in the UK
[normal] report, m
[normal]easuring the return on innovation RD&amp;D programmes is complex, not least due to inter-linkages 
[normal]with deployment support and other policies, though there is some evidence
[normal] that such programmes can result in significant returns.
[normal]32.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The LCICG have developed a common set of seven low carbon energy innovation metrics
[normal] which are being piloted
[normal].  The metrics 
[normal]aim
[normal] to
[normal] 
[normal]evaluate the impact and outcomes the LCICG’s programmes have had against the core themes of 
[normal]delivering: affordable, secure, low carbon energy for the UK; UK economic growth; and the UK’s capabilities, knowledge and skills.
[normal]33.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The metrics will 
[normal]aim to 
[normal]ident
[normal]ify projects 
[normal]and programmes 
[normal]in which significant cost reduction or improved efficiency has been achieved. By tracking the estimated costs of technologies we 
[normal]look to
[normal] 
[normal]show progress towards commercial viability. 
[normal]The vision is for 
[normal]LCICG 
[normal]to
[normal] 
[normal]use this data to loo
[normal]k for longer-term evidence that LCICG-supported innovations are having a beneficial impact on cost reductions in commercial technology.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]34.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The metrics 
[normal]look to
[normal] 
[normal]capture the contribution of the LCICG to UK growth, where commercial sales or increased company val
[normal]uation occurs within 3 years of receiving LCICG support. 
[normal]Increased international sales also contribute to this measure. 
[normal] For
[normal] less commercial technologies, by tracking estimated years to market the LCICG can forecast when it expects economic impact to occur
[normal].  
[normal]Analysis will 
[normal]support 
[normal]the LCICG to spot valleys of death in technology sub areas which has not been possible with a top down approach.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]35.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The LCICG needs to 
[normal]enable
[normal] a healthy UK innovation system if it is to succeed in delivering 
[normal]its
[normal] aims. 
[normal]Adoption of t
[normal]he metrics will measure the generation of unique knowledge and inventions, the mobilisation of financial capital and perceived UK skills gaps. 
[normal]It
[normal] will also
[normal] support
[normal] identify where LCICG collaborations have 
[normal]precipitated new innovation ac
[normal]tivity and identify k
[normal]ey players in the landscape.
[normal]36.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In addition to the LCICG metrics
[normal],
[normal] individual members adopt 
[normal]in-house 
[normal]evaluation processes to measure their programmes successes against their original objectives.   
[normal]Thi
[normal]s section aims to provide evidence against the Committee’s
[normal] [bold]question
[normal] 
[normal]5
[normal]: 
[normal]What is the impact of the short-term funding timelines on private sector investment?
[normal]37.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]UK Government investment leverages substantial funding from other sources and private sector funding
[normal] for development or demonstration projects usually matches or exceeds the government investment.
[normal]  The balance of 
[normal]public and private 
[normal]funding is dependent on the project type
[normal] and European State Aid limits.
[normal]38.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Private investment in low carbon generation and 
[normal]energy efficiency technologies plays a crucial role in innovation, and is influenced by expected returns, the cost of capital and its availability, the degree of regulatory certainty, perceived risks (demand, technological and political), and the extent to
[normal] which firms can enter and exit markets with ease. Al
[normal]t
[normal]ogether, a ‘productive ecosystem’ is required to encourage innovation, including conditions in which risks can be understood, managed and anticipated. For conventional private funds, 
[normal]such as commercial 
[normal]banks, 
[normal]which generally have a low appetite for risk, the uncertainties inherent in the development of energy technologies will often be sufficiently large to dissuade investment.
[normal] 
[normal]39.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The LCICG members seek to reduce these risks by offering a range of interve
[normal]ntions which may benefit different innovations such as capital grants, equity investment and incubation.  The members also play a different role in the commercialisation of technologies at different stages of development.  
[normal]40.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Innovation, particularly in the 
[normal]e
[normal]nergy sector, can take a long time. Most public sector funding for low carbon
[normal] innovation 
[normal]is constrained by the 
[normal]spending r
[normal]ound timetables which limit commitments beyond the current spending round. This lack of long term certainty that support will be avail
[normal]able can be a barrier to investment by private sector innovators. Some public-sector 
[normal]backed bodies such as 
[normal]the Energy Technologies Institute and the Catapult Centres and 
[normal]have
[normal],
[normal] however
[normal],
[normal] been able to plan activities on 
[normal]a 
[normal]long
[normal]er time horizon. 
[normal]41.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]UK 
[normal]Governme
[normal]nt’s industrial strategies
[normal],
[normal] published in 2013
[normal],
[normal] set out how 
[normal]government aims to overcome specific barriers faced by businesses developing their technologies, including for the offshore wind, construction and nuclear sectors.  These include access to finance;
[normal] partnerships with sectors; support for emerging technologies; creating a pipeline of skilled workers; and government procurement to support the development of supply chains.
[normal] 
[normal]Some specific 
[normal]recent 
[normal]examples:
[normal]42.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In addition to the UK industrial strategies 
[normal]Scotland developed 
[normal]specific strategies for its key strategic sectors such as the 
[normal]Offshore Wind Ro
[normal]ute Map.
[normal]43.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Many
[normal] low carbon
[normal] innovations are driven by 
[normal]very small businesses
[normal] which can
[normal]no
[normal]t raise capital from banks as their businesses are pre-revenue
[normal] generating
[normal].  They often seek support from Angel or 
[normal]V
[normal]enture 
[normal]C
[normal]apital 
[normal]investors.  The public low carbon innovati
[normal]on landscape offers a range of solutions to support different type of businesses, third sector organisations and academia 
[normal]to 
[normal]get the support they need, 
[normal]mainly in the form of
[normal] capital grants
[normal] and
[normal] procuring their 
[normal]technology
[normal] but also to a lesser extent equity and business incubation
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]44.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It is through coordinated 
[normal]a
[normal]nd strategic investment that government can catalyse greater levels of private sector innovation and unlock the resources required to achieve improved efficiencies and
[normal] reduced costs for low carbon technologies, while delivering economic benefits from growing businesses and supply chains
[normal].
[normal]45.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]  
[normal]The 
[normal]Technology Strategy Board
[normal] and RCUK
[normal] are developing 
[normal]the 
[normal]concept 
[normal]of an ‘energy catalyst’ fund that could support the best new energ
[normal]y technologies from concept all the way through to commercialisation in a continuous manner and at the time when needed.  This kind of mechanism could provide greater certainty of public support to low carbon technology developers.
[normal]  
[normal]For example, t
[normal]he RCUK a
[normal]nd TSB are to launch the Industrial Biotechnology Catalyst (IB Catalyst) in January 2014.  The IB Catalyst will fund proposals to support the early translation of research (including gaseous and liquid biofuels) from groups led by academics only, academic-
[normal]industrial collaborations and industrialists.   
