[normal]The NAO’s
[normal] 
[normal]report into Public funding for innovatio
[normal]n in low carbon technologies in the UK
[normal],
[normal] stated that DECC’s spending in 2011/12 and 2012/13 was substantially less than budgeted and that the department was looking to accelerate spending in 2013/14 and 2014/15.
[normal]  The report stated that DECC had forecast (ca
[normal]pital and programme) spend for four year spending review of £173.2m against a budget of £181m.
[normal]81.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]DECC’s
[normal] technology
[normal] innovation 
[normal]“
[normal]calls
[normal]” or “requests for proposals”
[normal] requ
[normal]ire
[normal] companies to submit bids for funding.  Funding is 
[normal]distributed
[normal] on the basis of the best i
[normal]deas
[normal], 
[normal]which fit with
[normal] the objectives of the
[normal] specific call
[normal] while aligning with DECC’s broader agenda, and offer value for money, rather
[normal] than 
[normal]fully utilising the DECC innovation
[normal] budget.
[normal]82.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Innovation projects are innately ris
[normal]ky and challenging to forecast becaus
[normal]e they are unique and dealing with unknowns in 
[normal]their 
[normal]development and construction. F
[normal]lexibility to adapt to the realities of the project as it develops is important to maximise the chances of successful delivery. Part of the challenge for the 
[normal]programme managers 
[normal]is to track the comm
[normal]itted funding levels and actual 
[normal]spend 
[normal]while making
[normal] adjustments and trade-offs between 
[normal]projects
[normal] to maximise
[normal] value for money
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]while
[normal] ensuring we can fund as many good projects as possible. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]83.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]DECC’s initial innovation bud
[normal]get profile 
[normal]allocation from the spending review settlement 
[normal]was identified as being suboptimal 
[normal]and was modified
[normal] 
[normal]to become
